The antithyroid agents market can be segmented based on drug type, route of administration, and distribution channel. In terms of drug type, the market is divided into thionamide derivatives, iodine salts, and others. Thionamide derivatives are widely used in the treatment of hyperthyroidism as they inhibit the production of thyroid hormones. Iodine salts are also commonly prescribed to manage hyperthyroidism by reducing the production of thyroid hormones. The market is further segmented by route of administration, including oral and injectable formulations. Oral administration is the most preferred route for antithyroid agents due to ease of use and patient compliance. Injectable formulations are used in cases where oral medications are not effective or well-tolerated. Lastly, the distribution channel segment includes hospital pharmacies, retail pharmacies, and online pharmacies where patients can access antithyroid medications conveniently.

